    <p class="lead">General Information on the Interface Status Register (ISR)</p>
    <h3>Overview</h3>
    <p>The ISR (Interface Status Register) collects all information required for the project's
    Interface Management. It supports the responsible Interface Manager (IFM) to guide and control
    all tasks during the Interface Management processes. Further major process participants are the
    Interface Leader (IFL) and the Interface Partner (IFP). Other users may have access to the status
    information or details of the interface.</p>
    <h3>Principles</h3>
    <div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-4">
    <%= image_tag 'isr_drawing_01.png', alt: 'Interface Data Structure', class: 'img-responsive' -%>
    </div>
    <div class="col-sm-8">
    <p>There are two major levels of Interface Management implemented here: <strong>Interfaces</strong>
    (IF - elsewhere in <a href=#refs>literature</a> called 'Interface Points' (IP)) and
    <strong>Interface Agreements (IA)</strong>.</p>
    <p>In general, <strong>Interfaces</strong> are the shared boundaries across two separate, independent
    but interacting systems, organizations, stakeholders, project phases and scopes, and construction elements.
    Another definition describes an Interface as a soft and/or hard contact point between two independent
    interface stakeholders. An Interface is also often a definition of part of the project's scope split
    as defined by project agreements.</p>
    <p>In technical terms, an Interface is the physical, functional, or communication boundary between
    two (or more) adjacent elements. Sometimes, this may be reduced to the boundary between two physical
    objects as parts of a technical system.</p>
    <p>An <strong>Interface Agreement</strong> is a formal and documented communication between two
    interface stakeholders (the 'Interface Partners'), including the deliverable description, need dates,
    and required actions. The Interface Agreement is often supplemented with tasks/activities that
    need to be performed to provide the agreement deliverables (<strong>Resolution Steps</strong>). 
    Additional validation tasks (<strong>Validation Steps</strong>) may be agreed to ensure the correct
    implementation of the agreed interface.</p>
    <p>Supporting documentation (drawings, specifications, etc.) may be created to illustrate the interface 
    and any agreed solution specifics.</p>
    <p>In the simple case, we are dealing with a single Interface and a single Interface Agreement. In this
    case, a differentiation between Interface and Interface Agreement may be neglected: When discussing the
    IF, we can discuss the IA regarding this IF at the same time. Here, IF and IA can be treated as single
    set of data.</p>
    </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-6">
    <p>In more complex situations, an IA may need be split into several IAs: For example, the initial
    IA was made among the consortium members before the start of a project. Later, the project's scope
    was split into several lots, and the initial (consortium level) IA must be re-negotiated with the
    new lots, possibly resulting in different deadlines for the deliverables, or even a different 
    solution of the IF.</p>
    <p>Once the new IAs have been agreed upon with each new lot, the original IA can be marked as
    'superseded by specific IAs'.</p>
    <p>In addition, we must consider that IAs might need to be revised, i.e. a former IA requires a
    revision of the original IA. In this case, the new IA will eventually replace the previous IA. The
    previous IA can be marked as 'superseded by revision'.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="col-sm-6">
    <%= image_tag 'isr_drawing_02.png', alt: 'Interface Agreements Scenario 1', class: 'img-responsive' -%>
    </div>
    </div>
    <p><strong>Resolution Steps</strong> and <strong>Validation Steps</strong> are each an IA-specific list
    of action items. These action items will be followed up item by item with item-specific deadlines.</p>
    <h3>Interface Status Register (ISR)</h3>
    <p>The ISR (Interface Status Register) is the central point of access for all interface-related information:
    The ISR contains the description of all IFs in the project and their attributes. All IAs associated with
    a specific IF can be located there as well. Resolutions and Validation Steps are maintained separately
    as IA-specific Task/Issue/Action Item Lists. The ISR provides management information about the overall
    status on IFs and IAs, specifically by providing various statistics on IFs and IAs.</p>
    <p>The administration of IFs and IAs is implemented as workflows, each workflow consisting of a network
    of tasks. Access to certain attributes and functions are restricted to those accounts having the
    respective permissions.</p>
    <h3>Types of Interfaces</h3>
    <div class="row">
    <div class="col-sm-6">
    <%= image_tag 'isr_drawing_03.png', alt: 'Types of Interface', class: 'img-responsive' -%>
    </div>
    <div class="col-sm-6">
    <p>The scope of supply, as specified in the tender or contract, is provided by several companies and
    sub-contractors. Each member of the project delivers one or more sub-systems of the total scope. The
    drawing 'Types of Interfaces' depicts the different types of IFs which can be object of the
    Interface Management processes:</p>
    <p><strong>External Interfaces</strong> (or 'Extra-Project Interfaces') are IFs between a sub-system
    delivered by one of the project partners and systems supplied by the client or other external parties;
    for example, power utility, water utility, telephone company, property owners, and the like.
    As these parties have no contractual relationship to the project, any IF must be clarified under the
    sole responsibility of the involved/effected sub-system. As no binding IA can be formally agreed,
    all activities to resolve the IF must be handled by the effected sub-system alone.</p>
    <p><strong>Internal Interfaces</strong> (or 'Inter-Project Interfaces') are IFs between different 
    sub-systems within the project scope.
    This is the classical case for IAs - formal agreements between legal entities on how an IF is resolved.
    The leading sub-system has the responsibility to drive all actions required to close any Interface
    Resolution and Validation Steps.</p>
    <p><strong>Sub-System Internal Interfaces</strong> (or 'Intra-Project Interfaces') are IFs within
    a sub-system. Although such IFs may not require a formal agreement to be resolved, it might be a useful
    idea to track the resolution of these interfaces using the same methods and processes as for (project)
    Internal Interfaces.</p>
    <p>The type of an Interface effects some of the implemented workflows: An IF without a formal IA must
    allow the IFL to follow the workflow steps without actual involvment of the IFP. 
    </div>
    </div>
